illion prisoners today. In policing the line between "bad criminal" and "good citizen," the carceral system has shaped and reshaped Iranian understandings of citizenship, freedom, and political belonging. Golnar Nikpour explores the interplay between the concrete space of the Iranian prison and the role of prisons in producing new public cultures and political languages in Iran. From prison writings of 1920s leftist prisoners and communiqués of 1950s militant Islamists, to paintings of 1970s revolutionary guerrillas and mapping projects organized by contemporary dissident prisoners, carceral confinement has shaped modern Iranian political movements. Today, mass incarceration is a global phenomenon. The Incarcerated Modern connects Iranian history to transnational carceral histories to illuminate the shared architectures, economies, and techniques of modern punishment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPrisonsxPolitical aspectszIran2DLC. 0aPrisonsxPolitical aspectszIran. 0aPrisonszIranxHistory2DLC. 0aPrisonszIranxHistory. 0aPunishmentzIranxHistory2DLC. 0aPunishmentzIranxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Iran.2bisacsh  aIslamic Revolution.  aPahlavi Iran.  aPrisons.  aQajar Persia.  acriminology.  acritical prison studies.  ahuman rights.  amodern Iran.  aprison abolition.  atorture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079133440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363764140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503637641423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503637641/original  a978-3-11-079133-4  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles